I also have an obsession with the symbolism of a 'clean slate start', as in, waiting till a certain time before starting over completely, rather than fixing problems as they crop up on the fly.
Yeah, self-motivation isn't easy and doesn't just come to everyone in spades.
I don't think there's anything unique about what you're feeling.
I'm terrified of myself. But I don't want to change either, because I'm terrified that it'd be too much effort, and that I'd make the wrong decisions.
Plus, I keep beating myself up over every tiny thing.
This entire conversation is just a case in point.
Hmm... I understand what you're getting at.
Well, my parents and I have agreed I'm going to see a therapist.
I keep looking at the week ahead with dread...
Exams, all my life, have been a major Achilles Heel for me.
I suppose all I'm doing now is looking for more distractions from reality till the stream comes...
Any advice I try to give you isn't some magic, I don't really know any better or anything
But, for me, family, friends, exercise...
Finding something productive to do, even if it's not much

Cyclic error cyclic error cyclic error...
Sorry, just typing them to remember
Occurs where constant point is misaligned with tripod centre point
I'd forgotten that for ages, now I know it again.
I thought you meant Electronic Dance Music lol
Electronic levels, Electronic total stations etc.
They use a variable wavelength laser beam from a Gallium Arsenide Diode to measure distance.
one source of error is that clocks have to be synced exactly.
How those instruments work is literal lasers and math
Not when you're carrying £5'000 worth of equipment in a box
Anyhow, there are three main error sources to worry about
Cyclic error is an error repeated through the wavelength, not distance dependent
Scale error is distance dependent-arises from an incorrect modulation
You measure 1654m but only use a 10m amplitude modulation
You have to use a 10'000m Amplitude Modulation to get the full thing
Sorry about the walls of text.
But that's actually a major section of the exam studied for.
I'll probably be asked to explain those sorts of errors and suchlike.
Oh yeah-surveying instruments can also be affected by electromagnetic radiation, refraction, atmospheric factors (such as humidity) and suchlike.
There is no such thing as 100% accuracy here.
There are bound to be tiny erros that slip through.
The job is to make sure that they are as tiny as possible.
My mentor when I started engineering loved to say "Good enough"
Because a 5mm error in the plans for building a bridge can be an absolute catastrophe.
And that's something I need to hit myself on the head with.

Maybe a difference between measurement and design.  Measurements always should be as good as reasonable (certainly small enough error to do the job).  Design can always be better, but if it meets the requirements, eventually, it's good enough.
You have requirements in surveying, which you have to meet.
My mentors say that on a bridge building site, a pillar might constantly be warping either direction by a fraction.
As a result, they are always watching with the total station.
Oh they will be.  The design better account for that imperfection
And instructing the workers to make adjustments as they go.
There are also 3 laser EDMs which use three lasers of varying wavelengths to cancel out errors in each particular length.
